      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1846_05_10_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Vicarage. Trim.</placeName>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">Rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> R Butlers</persName>
                  <date when="1846-05-10"/>May 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1846</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Sir</persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I am much obliged by your<lb/>
                    present of second series of<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RushR1">Rush's</persName>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Resid1">Residence at the<lb/>
                        Court of London</title>. I have<lb/>
                    read it with much pleasure<lb/>
                    - My impression is that it<lb/>
                    is an admirable example<lb/>
                    of diplomatic memoir<lb/>
                    writing - at once safe &amp; <lb/>
                    honorable and <choice>
                  <orig>wonder-<lb/>
                        fully</orig>
                  <reg>wonderfully</reg>
               </choice> entertaining <choice>
                  <orig>consi<lb/>
                            dering</orig>
                  <reg>considering</reg>
               </choice> that it is both safe<lb/>
                    and honorable, betraying<lb/>
                    no private confidence, nor<lb/>
                    public trust, giving no <choice>
                  <orig>um-<lb/>
                        brage</orig>
                  <reg>umbrage</reg>
               </choice> to either court or country- <lb/>
                    - Giving to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName> a good<lb/>
                    idea of our country, and giv
                    ing good natured <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BullJ1">John Bull</persName>
               <choice>
                  <orig>conse-<lb/>
                        quently</orig>
                  <reg>consequently</reg>
               </choice> a more friendly <choice>
                  <orig>inc<lb/>
                     <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1846_05_10_page02.jpg"/>
                    
                    clination</orig>
                  <reg>inclination</reg>
               </choice> towards <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Jona1">Jonathan</persName>
               <lb/>
               <unclear/> - after all! - </p>
            <p> The sheep shearing at <choice>
                  <orig>Hol<lb/>
                    kam</orig>
                  <reg>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Holkham_ENK">Holkam</placeName>
                  </reg>
               </choice> is graphically described<lb/>
                    and gives a superb idea<lb/>
                    to foreigners of our English King<lb/>
                    of Gentleman farmers &amp; residence<lb/>
                    and hospitable doings<lb/>
                    such as no other country<lb/>
                    on this globe ever before<lb/>
                    exhibited! <lb/>
            </p>
            <p> The <del>dinner at </del>] <add>minister</add> after dinner<lb/>
                    conversation where the<lb/>
                    game of 24 questions was<lb/>
                    so well played with Canning,<lb/>
                    is excellent - harmlessly<lb/>
                    entertaining - and <choice>
                  <orig>charac<lb/>
                        teristic</orig>
                  <reg>characteristic</reg>
               </choice> of the playful <choice>
                  <orig>sim<lb/>
                            -plicity</orig>
                  <reg>simplicity</reg>
               </choice> of real genius that<lb/>
                    dares to amuse &amp; be amused<lb/>
                    in right season - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p> The <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WellC1">Duchess of Wellington</persName>
               <lb/>
                    is mentioned by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RushR1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Rush</persName>
               <lb/>
                    with <del>more</del> truth and the<lb/>
                    representation <unclear>more</unclear>
               <choice>
                  <orig>resem<lb/>
                        -bles</orig>
                  <reg>resembles</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1846_05_10_page03.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WellC1">her <hi rend="underline">Grace</hi>
               </persName> than any portrait<lb/>
                    or attempt to pourtray her<lb/>
                    I ever saw - she speaks<lb/>
                    for herself and that is<lb/>
                    all her best friends could<lb/>
                    wish - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p> I am gratified &amp; obliged <lb/>
                    by your manner of <choice>
                  <orig>men<lb/>
                        - tioning</orig>
                  <reg>mentioning</reg>
               </choice> my writings - <lb/>
                    I am ashamed to answer<lb/>
                    your inquiry as to when<lb/>
                    I shall probably finish what<lb/>
                    I am writing - From<lb/>
                    ill health and various<lb/>
                    causes too tedious &amp; senseless <lb/>
                    to mention I have not<lb/>
                    advanced as I ought -<lb/>
                    I have no <add>little</add> prospect at <choice>
                  <orig>pre -<lb/>
                        sent</orig>
                  <reg>present</reg>
               </choice> of coming to that<lb/>
                    happy word Finis this<lb/>
                    year - and being in my<lb/>
                    79<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> year - I leave you<lb/>
                    to judge of the rest<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
                    I am <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ButlR1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Sir</persName>yours truly
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
